    <p><strong>Astrophysical jets</strong> are collimated outflows launched from accreting compact objects or young stars. They transport energy and momentum over large distances and interact with the ambient medium, producing shocks and non-thermal emission.</p>

    <h2>Background</h2>
    <p>Jets appear across scales from protostars to microquasars to active galactic nuclei (AGN). Launching mechanisms include magneto-centrifugal disk winds and black-hole spin extraction (e.g., Blandford–Payne, Blandford–Znajek).</p>

    <h2>Physical description</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Structure</strong> — A fast collimated core (jet) surrounded by a shocked cocoon formed by interaction with the ambient medium.</li>
      <li><strong>Collimation</strong> — External pressure from the cocoon or ambient medium can recollimate expanding jets, creating standing recollimation shocks.</li>
      <li><strong>Scale dependence</strong> — Jet power, velocity, and environment set the morphology and radiative signatures.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why this matters</h2>
    <p>Jets are candidate accelerators of cosmic rays and producers of high-energy photons and neutrinos. Recollimation shocks in jets can be persistent acceleration sites; see [[recollimation-shocks]] and [[jet-cocoon-systems]].</p>

    <h2>Key references</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Bromberg et al. 2011 — analytic framework for jet–cocoon interactions (used and extended by 2603.16647).</li>
    </ol>

